The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine and elsewhere are constantly in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
Yet this turns out to be a big mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It is obvious that everyone would gladly end war and violence, just as we would gladly put an end to poverty, hunger, and global warming and provide all people with access to education.
However, due to limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities and for this, one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be the wisest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that could otherwise, for example, be spent on fighting hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at the University of Oxford, violence within society – murders and, in particular, violence against women and children – is a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die due to interpersonal violence, and for every two fighters who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs one person's life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against the global income, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GDP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but a way of expressing the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be in a better position, measurable at 1.7% of the GDP.
Compare this with the clearly lower costs of civil wars, which amount to about 0.2% of the world's GDP.
This is still, however, much less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence by their life partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, married off at a young age, exposed to sexual violence, and became victims of crimes committed in the name of "honor" and female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the resulting costs for society alone from violence by partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is the abuse of children, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but about 15% of children experience what the UN describes as severe corporal punishment every month.
This includes blows to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are beaten repeatedly and as hard as possible with an object.
This suffering affects about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
Only a tiny fraction of international aid money is currently flowing into reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals scream for action.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any reliable insights as to where the limited resources should best be used.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more specifically.
Large sums of aid money are allocated to "fragile states" in order to contribute to ending or preventing civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component of "crime prevention".
Other programs may contribute indirectly, yet obviously much could be improved.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of care and procedural costs.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 U.S. dollars: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program called SASA! is working in Uganda.
(Swahili for "Now!") to spread the message that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
That is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost-effectiveness available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – a time limit for the sale of alcohol, reclaiming public space, and improvements in the police and justice system – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of major importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We still do not know enough, but two things are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children entails costs for society amounting to 8 trillion U.S. dollars per year and thus represents a huge – and far too little noticed – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence belongs among the shortlist for the next global development goals.
